CODE GENERATION (REQUIRED for every spec — implementation_mode is always
"generated_class")

Emit a **single** Python class named **GeneratedStrategy** that subclasses `StrategyBase`.

**Hard rules (violations will crash the backtest):**
- NO import statements — use only: `pd`, `np`, `StrategyBase`, `Signal`, and these
  functions: `ema`, `sma`, `wma`, `supertrend`, `adx`, `rsi`, `macd`, `stochastic`,
  `roc`, `atr`, `bollinger_bands`, `keltner_channel`, `vwap`, `obv`, `calculate_heikin_ashi`,
  plus research chart-pattern helpers (same logic as `marketapi_data_fetcher/algo_methods/patterns/`):
  `find_hs_patterns`, `HSPattern`, `hs_pattern_return` (head & shoulders),
  `find_all_pivot_points`, `find_doubles_pattern` (double tops/bottoms). OHLC columns must be lowercase.
- Define `name = "custom_<short_snake_case_hint>"`, `description`, `default_params` dict,
  optionally `param_ranges = {}` for future optimiser support, `prepare(self, df)`, and
  `on_bar(self, i, row, df) -> Signal | None`.
- Signals: `Signal("buy"|"sell"|"exit", reason="...", sl=float|None, tp=float|None)`.
- Never call open(), exec(), eval(), __import__, etc.

Abbreviated pattern:
```python
class GeneratedStrategy(StrategyBase):
    name = "custom_my_strategy"
    description = "..."
    default_params = {"ema_fast": 9, "ema_slow": 21}
    param_ranges = {}
    def prepare(self, df):
        out = df.copy()
        out["ema_f"] = ema(df, self.params["ema_fast"])
        ...
        return out
    def on_bar(self, i, row, df):
        ...
        return None
```

**Position state — read this carefully, getting it wrong silently produces 0
trades.** ``self.position`` is a `Position` dataclass with these fields:

    self.position.side         # "flat" | "long" | "short"
    self.position.entry_price  # float
    self.position.size         # float
    self.position.sl           # float | None
    self.position.tp           # float | None

To check whether you're already in a trade, use the ``.side`` field directly:

    if self.position.side == "flat":     # no position → consider entry
        if entry_long_condition:
            return Signal("buy", reason="...")
        elif entry_short_condition:
            return Signal("sell", reason="...")
    elif self.position.side == "long":   # in a long → consider exit
        if exit_condition:
            return Signal("exit", reason="...")
    elif self.position.side == "short":  # in a short → consider exit
        if exit_condition:
            return Signal("exit", reason="...")

DO NOT write ``if self.position == 0:`` or ``if self.position > 0:`` — those
are MetaTrader / numeric-state idioms and they will silently never fire here
because ``self.position`` is an object, not a signed integer. Always use
``self.position.side``.

DataFrame indexing inside ``on_bar``:

The backtest engine resets ``df`` to an integer index before passing it to your
strategy, so ``i`` is a position 0..N-1 and **both** of these work for the
current bar's column ``"ema_fast"``:

    df.loc[i, "ema_fast"]      # ✓ label-based — i is now an int label
    df.iloc[i]["ema_fast"]     # ✓ positional
    row["ema_fast"]            # ✓ same row as a Series, fastest

For the previous bar use any of:

    df.loc[i - 1, "ema_fast"]  # ✓ as long as i >= 1
    df.iloc[i - 1]["ema_fast"]
    df["ema_fast"].iloc[i - 1]

Pick one style and stay consistent. Always guard with ``if i < 1: return None``
before reading ``i - 1``.

Put the **entire** class in JSON string `generated_python` with proper escaping
(`\n` newlines). `generated_python` is REQUIRED and must be non-empty for every
spec.

